A masterpiece by @aaronbheff for International Day of Disabled People.

To disabled people everywhere, on the good days & the shit ones, when you feel like you can take on the world & when all you can do is lay in bed, I'll always be over here being your biggest cheerleader.🖤

#IDPWD #DisabilityRepresentation #disabled #disability #SpinaBifida #scoliosis #sketch #art

Some days I'm on fire, working on a million different things with a camera in my face, & some days I only have enough energy to work from my bed. My disability does this to me sometimes & that's where we are today.

So here's me, in bed, surrounded by cushions with the hound (reluctantly) acting as my secretary.*

 *Performance Review: chews on snacks a little too loudly, constantly sleeping on the job, would not hire again.

#disability #chronic #SpinaBifida #scoliosis

OMG. LOOK. AT. HER.

Dad surprised me yesterday with the new Chelsea doll... and she has scoliosis!!

I was diagnosed with scoliosis at 18 months & had to wear a spinal brace from then up until I was a teenager. I lived for Barbies when I was a kid & if this Chelsea doll had been available back then, it would've meant the world to little me. Things like this may seem small & insignificant to some people, but body positivity & acceptance is just as important for young kids as it is for adults. Toys like this would definitely have helped me with mine growing up. 

Thank you @mattel for showing kids that all bodies are beautiful & valid. 

Chelsea has now joined the squad on my desk. 💕

#Barbie #scoliosis #DisabledBodyGoodness #BodyPositivity #SpinalBrace #DisabilityRepresentation

RTS AWARDS 🥂

Forever proud of our 'Then Barbara Met Alan' family, nominated for Best Single Drama at last night's awards.

We made this film to tell the story of the people behind the Direct Action Network who changed the laws on disability discrimination in Britain in the 90s, & I've never been prouder to be part of such an important show.

Disabled stories are vital. They change the way shows are made for the better. They flip the narrative on who the industry believes can lead stories & they challenge people's preconceptions about what being disabled actually means. 

I'm honoured to be in rooms where disabled stories are recognised & celebrated, & I'm more determined than ever to make sure the doors to those rooms stay open for the next generation of disabled talent.

'Then Barbara Met Alan' & the incredible team behind it will stay in my heart forever. "Piss on Pity!"

A week ago, we came back from the most incredible trip to Orlando. Thank you so much to our friends at @disneyparksuk for giving us a magical time at The Contemporary Resort & treating us like Disney Royalty. We are so lucky & so unbelievably grateful. 

Access is a huge issue for travellers who are disabled, & me & Joe have had our fair share of trouble, but Disney never fails us. We've never once had to worry about accessible bathrooms, hotels or restaurants while we've been there, & the Disney Parks are beyond perfect for me as a wheelchair-user. So thank you to @nikkipalmas @lydia.lancaster & the whole Disney Parks team for giving us time to enjoy a fully accessible world. 

@theboy_888 @waltdisneyworld @disneyscontemporaryresort

A few years ago, when our show won a BAFTA, I had to be carried on stage behind a curtain because there was no ramp. On Sunday night, I was back on that exact same stage presenting the BAFTA for Supporting Actress alongside Ben Whishaw, only this time, it was fully accessible.

Disabled people deserve access at every level of our industry, including awards ceremonies. Making spaces like this accessible means that you expect disabled talent to be in the room, you expect them to be accepting & presenting awards, & you acknowledge that they're a key part of our industry. 

Thank you @bafta for inviting me to present an award & for recognising the importance of access. Never underestimate what this means. 

(As a side note: I'm very much in love with Ben & Anne-Marie Duff.)

Scoliosis B-roll by my love @khandiz 

Here are some questions I get asked a lot about my scoliosis:

Have I had surgery? - Yes. I've had metal rods put in (too many bloody times) to try & straighten the curve in my spine.

Does it hurt? - Hell yeah... nerve pain is a bitch. But some days are a lot better than others. 

Am I like the bionic woman? Obviously. 

Shout out to all my fellow bionic women & men who carry their metal/mettle around with them every day. 🤟🏻

A list of things I'll be doing this Disability Pride Month: 

Enjoying the sunshine, eating & drinking stuff that makes me happy, laughing (a lot), doing a job that I love, managing pain levels, resting (as much as possible), dealing with inaccessibility (same shit, different day), celebrating the glorious things that disabled people around me are doing, & finally... trying my best, every day, to live fearlessly in my disabled body in a world that tells me I shouldn't.

"I'd rather be dead than be in a wheelchair for the rest of my life." 

This is a direct quote that was said to my face in a work environment, in front of a room full of people. 

If you ever wonder why Disability Pride is so important, it's because there are people who see my body & my life as their worst-case scenario. And it always amazes me just how comfortable people can be in telling me so.

But disability isn't my worst-case scenario & I will never allow it to be.

They can say they'd choose death, but me? I choose life. Every. Single. Time.

#DisabilityPride #DisabilityTruths #disability #DisabilityPrideMonth #DisabledLife #WheelchairUser #DisabledBodyGoodness

🗣️ “The skills I have learnt, the confidence to unashamedly ask for whatever you want, and to believe that you can achieve whatever you want — Whizz Kidz played a huge part in that. I always say that I would never ever be doing this without them. No way”

Ruth Madeley was five when Whizz Kidz turned her into “Barbie on wheels”.

The charity provided her with a bright pink wheelchair, which her father had been prepared to take a bank loan out to buy. It launched a lifelong friendship that continued even after Madeley became more Doctor Who than Barbie.

The Times and The Sunday Times are joining forces and urging readers to dig deep for three charities in this year’s Christmas appeal.

Visit http://thetimes.co.uk/christmasappeal to donate and help Whizz Kids, Feeding Britain and Street Child to carry out their vital work

📸 Christopher L Proctor for The Times / BBC

To all my disabled creatives, here's a little January message from me that I hope you'll all remember this year...

Whether you're already in the industry or just starting out, please try not to listen to the noise that so often surrounds us as disabled people. 

All too often, we're not given the same grace as others to simply be good at what we do & have the chance to just enjoy it. We have to be good at what we do (sometimes exceptionally good) &, on top of that, be able to handle the noise of those who say we're only there to "fill a quota." 

But noise is all it is. Meaningless noise that I hope with all my heart you're able to drown out.

When you land a job this year (which you will - I can feel it), you won't be a tick box exercise, a diversity hire, or the result of "woke agenda." You'll book the job because you were right for it, you were the best in the room, & because you damn well deserve it.

I know this gig is tough, but SO ARE YOU. Authentic disabled stories are vital. Disabled bodies on stage & screen are vital. Please always remember that you are allowed to be visible & take up space. You don't need permission. 

I hope this year brings you so many opportunities to show the world exactly what you bring to the party, & I'll be your biggest hypegirl toasting all of your successes, big or small.

Let's have it. 💋

📸 - @jemimashoots

#Disability ##DisabilityRepresentation #industry #DisabledPower ##DisabledBodyGoodness
